    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_951061675" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/951061675" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31533844-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617809291p2/31533844.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/951061675?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/31533844-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670025138" href="/book/show/13589162-the-tale-of-the-heike">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31533844-sarah?shelf=japanese-lit">japanese-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31533844-sarah?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer951061675" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer342085357183915806">&quot;Springs ran blood; the dead lay in mounds.<br/>To this day, so it is told, <br/>arrow-strike nicks and sword cuts mark<br/>the rock up and down Kurikara.&quot;<br/><br/><i>The Tale of the Heike</i> is a lengthy, anonymous epic about the struggles of war between the Heike (Taira clan) and the Genji (Minamoto clan), resulting in the eventual downfall of the once-reigning Heike group. As well as being beautifully written in two forms of verse as well as prose (restored to original form by Royall Tyler in a fantastic translation), thi</span>
  <span id="freeText342085357183915806" style="display:none">"Springs ran blood; the dead lay in mounds.<br />To this day, so it is told, <br />arrow-strike nicks and sword cuts mark<br />the rock up and down Kurikara."<br /><br /><i>The Tale of the Heike</i> is a lengthy, anonymous epic about the struggles of war between the Heike (Taira clan) and the Genji (Minamoto clan), resulting in the eventual downfall of the once-reigning Heike group. As well as being beautifully written in two forms of verse as well as prose (restored to original form by Royall Tyler in a fantastic translation), this masterpiece of medieval Japanese literature is one of the most highly-regarded books on the art of war. In short, it is one of the staples of Japanese literature, equating with works such as <i>The Tale of Genji</i> and <i>The Pillow Book</i>. <br /><br />Unlike the less-violent <i>Tale of Genji</i>, <i>The Tale of the Heike</i> is very focused on the political and strategical side of war in a country that seemed to be fairly advanced in these situations. In <i>Genji</i>, the situations are strictly political and social, but <i>Heike</i> is all about war, which probably was not uncommon of the time, considering that there were many clan struggles in the development of the country. Although it is safe to say that the work is definitely romanticized (for example, Kenreimon-in's ascent to paradise), a lot of the accounts are definitely based on real-life people and events. <br /><br />Now to talk about the writing style and translation. Firstly, I was not surprised to find lots of beautiful verses and prose sections because all of the Japanese lit I have read so far is in possession of this. Even when writing about something as gritty and disgusting as war far (trust me, there are plenty of beheadings and suicides to go around), there is still elegance in descriptions, such as describing beautiful armor sets worn by warriors before battles, such as follows:<br /><br />"Yukiie, for his part, wore scarlet leather-laced armor over a dark blue brocade. A sword with gold fittings hung at his side, the arrows at his back were fletched in bold black and white bands..."<br /><br />Descriptions like these really bring into mind the fact that warriors were very much concerned with their own self-respect; there are many times when suicide is preferred over capture because of the humiliation that could be avoided through the former action.<br /><br />Royall Tyler does a fantastic job of restoring this work to a more accurate state, this time including recitatives and songs instead of just prose. One may think that this would be strange, but the format is satisfactory to read.<br /><br />Overall, this is a beautiful work that deserves to be read along with less warfare-based works like <i>Genji</i>- not only is it not completely fictional, but it shows a completely new side of Japanese history that cannot be gleaned from <i>Genji</i>. They both work together and should be read together.<br /><br />"Once you were to all, <br />in those days of long ago, <br />the moon in the sky, <br />who in this mountain village<br />dispels the darkness no more."</span>
  <a data-text-id="342085357183915806" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

